<div class="header">
  <div class="header-content">
    <div class="tag">Compiled by Gemini 3.1</div>
    <h1>Waste Management (WM)<br/>Intrinsic Value</h1>
    <p class="subtitle">A transparent, two-stage discounted cash flow valuation of Waste Management, Inc. — using FY2025 actuals, disclosed assumptions, and one final number.</p>
    <p class="date">Updated March 18, 2026 · Data: FY2025 10-K</p>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="container">
  <!-- ═══ THE VERDICT ═══ -->
  <div class="verdict-card">
    <div class="verdict-label">Estimated Intrinsic Value Per Share</div>
    <div class="verdict-price">${roundedIV.toFixed(2)}</div>
    <div class="verdict-vs">vs. market price of ${currentPrice.toFixed(2)} ({marginOfSafety}%)</div>
    <div class="verdict-badge" style={`background: ${verdictColor}22; color: ${verdictColor}; border: 1px solid ${verdictColor}44;`}>
      {verdictText}
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- ═══ KEY METRICS ═══ -->
  <div class="stats-row">
    <div class="stat-card">
      <div class="stat-value">${(revHist[0] / 1000).toFixed(1)}B</div>
      <div class="stat-label">FY2025 Revenue</div>
    </div>
    <div class="stat-card">
      <div class="stat-value">${(fcfHist[0] / 1000).toFixed(1)}B</div>
      <div class="stat-label">Free Cash Flow</div>
    </div>
    <div class="stat-card">
      <div class="stat-value">${epsHist[0].toFixed(2)}</div>
      <div class="stat-label">EPS (Diluted)</div>
    </div>
    <div class="stat-card">
      <div class="stat-value">{opMarginHist[0]}%</div>
      <div class="stat-label">Operating Margin</div>
    </div>
    <div class="stat-card">
      <div class="stat-value negative-val">${(netCash / 1000).toFixed(1)}B</div>
      <div class="stat-label">Net Cash</div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- ═══ METHODOLOGY ═══ -->
  <h2>Methodology: Two-Stage DCF</h2>
  <p>We use a <strong>two-stage discounted cash flow (DCF)</strong> model — the gold standard of intrinsic valuation. This model discounts all of Waste Management's future free cash flows back to today to determine what the business is worth, independent of short-term market sentiment.</p>

  <div class="method-step">
    <div class="step-num">1</div>
    <div class="step-content">
      <h4>Start with actual Free Cash Flow</h4>
      <p>Waste Management generated <strong>${(fcf2025 / 1000).toFixed(2)} billion</strong> in free cash flow in FY2025. This is operating cash flow minus capital expenditures. For an asset-heavy business like WM (which owns and operates landfills and fleets), FCF is the truest measure of profitability.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="method-step">
    <div class="step-num">2</div>
    <div class="step-content">
      <h4>Project FCF growth for 5 years (Phase 1)</h4>
      <p>We grow FCF at <strong>{(growthRatePhase1 * 100).toFixed(0)}% per year</strong> for 5 years. WM benefits from immense pricing power and inelastic demand—trash collection is an essential service. This steady growth rate reflects sustained volume pricing increases alongside operating efficiency gains, notably through automated fleets and renewable natural gas (RNG) initiatives.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="method-step">
    <div class="step-num">3</div>
    <div class="step-content">
      <h4>Calculate terminal value (Phase 2)</h4>
      <p>After Year 5, we assume FCF grows at <strong>{(growthRateTerminal * 100).toFixed(1)}% forever</strong>. Using the Gordon Growth Model, this captures all value from Year 6 to infinity. This terminal rate slightly exceeds long-term inflation, aligning with WM's historical ability to raise prices ahead of inflation.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="method-step">
    <div class="step-num">4</div>
    <div class="step-content">
      <h4>Discount everything to present value</h4>
      <p>All future cash flows are discounted at <strong>{(discountRate * 100).toFixed(1)}%</strong> — our required rate of return. This aligns with WM's relatively low risk profile and dominant market position (wide economic moat), balanced against the risk-free 10Y Treasury (4.18%).</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="method-step">
    <div class="step-num">5</div>
    <div class="step-content">
      <h4>Subtract net debt, divide by shares</h4>
      <p>Enterprise Value + Net Cash (${(netCash / 1000).toFixed(2)}B) = Equity Value. Since WM carries significant debt to finance its infrastructure, net cash is negative. We divide by shares outstanding ({sharesOutstanding}M) for the per-share intrinsic value.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- ═══ THE THREE ASSUMPTIONS ═══ -->
  <h2>The Three Assumptions That Drive Everything</h2>
  <p>A DCF is highly sensitive to its inputs. We focus on exactly <strong>three</strong> core assumptions. Here's what we chose and why.</p>

  <div class="assumption-grid">
    <div class="assumption-card">
      <div class="label">FCF Growth Rate (Years 1-5)</div>
      <div class="value">{(growthRatePhase1 * 100).toFixed(0)}%</div>
      <div class="rationale">
        WM's revenue growth reached roughly 14% in FY2025. We project a conservative 8% FCF growth. Their significant investments in recycling automation and RNG facilities demand high near-term CapEx, which dampens FCF growth initially, but yields high-margin returns over the 5-year phase.
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="assumption-card">
      <div class="label">Discount Rate (WACC)</div>
      <div class="value">{(discountRate * 100).toFixed(1)}%</div>
      <div class="rationale">
        With a 10Y Treasury at 4.18%, an 8.5% discount rate implies a reasonable equity risk premium for a highly defensive, wide-moat stock. WM operates in an oligopoly with immense regulatory barriers to entry (new landfills are rarely approved), making its cash flows highly predictable.
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="assumption-card">
      <div class="label">Terminal Growth Rate</div>
      <div class="value">{(growthRateTerminal * 100).toFixed(1)}%</div>
      <div class="rationale">
        Long-term nominal GDP growth is around 3%. WM's core business scales linearly with population growth and economic consumption. We assign a 3% terminal rate, assuming they can persistently match or slightly beat inflation via CPI-linked service contracts.
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

