  <p>The highlighted cell is our base case. Because WM's cash flows are stable, the valuation is exceptionally sensitive to the discount rate. If you demand a 10%+ return (a higher margin of safety), the stock appears heavily overvalued.</p>

  <!-- ═══ WHAT THE MODEL DOESN'T CAPTURE ═══ -->
  <h2>What This Model Doesn't Capture</h2>
  <p>No model is complete. Here's what a DCF inherently misses — and how it might bias our estimate.</p>

  <h3>Upside risks (our number could be too low)</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>RNG Monetization:</strong> WM is aggressively investing to convert landfill gas into renewable natural gas (RNG). If environmental credits and energy prices surge, these high-margin revenues could rapidly accelerate FCF.</li>
    <li><strong>Automation scaling:</strong> Continued deployment of single-operator collection vehicles and automated recycling facilities could compress labor costs more rapidly than projected.</li>
    <li><strong>Strategic Acquisitions:</strong> The model assumes organic growth. Given WM's fragmented competitive landscape, accretive tuck-in acquisitions could outpace baseline growth estimates.</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Downside risks (our number could be too high)</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Heavy debt load:</strong> WM carries over ${Math.round(totalDebt / 1000).toFixed(1)}B in debt. Prolonged elevated interest rates significantly increase refinancing costs, eating directly into future FCF.</li>
    <li><strong>Commodity pricing:</strong> Revenue from recycling operations is tied to global commodity prices for paper, plastic, and metals, which are highly cyclical.</li>
    <li><strong>Regulatory environment:</strong> Stringent new environmental regulations (e.g., PFAS "forever chemicals" disposal) could necessitate unanticipated, massive CapEx overhauls at existing landfills.</li>
  </ul>

  <!-- ═══ FAQ ═══ -->
  <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
  <div class="faq">
    <details>
      <summary>Why is net cash a negative number?</summary>
      <div class="faq-answer">Unlike asset-light tech companies, industrial infrastructure businesses like WM carry substantial long-term debt to finance massive capital assets (landfills, truck fleets). Their debt (${Math.round(totalDebt / 1000).toFixed(1)}B) heavily outweighs their cash on hand (${Math.round(cashAndInvestments / 1000).toFixed(1)}B). In our Equity Value calculation, this net debt is appropriately subtracted from the Enterprise Value.</div>
    </details>
    <details>
      <summary>Why use an 8.5% discount rate instead of 10%?</summary>
      <div class="faq-answer">Discount rates should reflect the riskiness of the business. Trash collection is non-cyclical, heavily contracted, and recession-resistant. Because the cash flows are highly reliable, investors typically demand a slightly lower required return (WACC) compared to highly volatile or speculative industries.</div>
    </details>
    <details>
      <summary>How does WM's moat affect the valuation?</summary>
      <div class="faq-answer">WM benefits from a "wide moat" driven by regulatory barriers. It is nearly impossible to acquire permitting for new landfills due to "Not In My Backyard" (NIMBY) opposition. This localized monopoly dynamic guarantees long-term utilization of their existing assets, allowing us to confidently assign a perpetual terminal growth rate.</div>
    </details>
    <details>
      <summary>Is this a buy recommendation?</summary>
      <div class="faq-answer">No. This is an analytical framework for estimating intrinsic value. Whether to buy depends on your personal risk tolerance, portfolio allocation, time horizon, tax situation, and conviction in the assumptions. We provide the tools and transparency — you make the decision.</div>
    </details>
  </div>

